Hepatitis B Vaccination Rates in the NICU and the Impact of a CDS Tool

BMIN5030 Final Project

Author

Alex Ruan

1 Overview

I am planning to use EHR (Epic, Clarity) data to look at the impact of a clinical decision support tool (Quality Improvement/Safety Rounding Checklist) used by four local neonatal intensive care units on a variety of clinical outcomes, such as vaccination, metabolic screen ordering, and central line days, among other clinical outcomes. Specifically, would hope to show via regression methods that the use of this tool has led to an improvement in these outcomes.

Two faculty mentors include:

Leah Carr, MD, Assistant Professor of Clinical Pediatrics, Attending Neonatologist and Clinical Informaticist, CHOP/Penn

Christopher Bonafide, MD, MSCE, Associate Professor of Pediatrics, CHOP/Penn

In discussion with my faculty mentors:

They suggested that I pare down my initial analysis to focus on one outcome as each one would be a hefty analysis. Specifically, after discussion, they recommended that I focus on hepatitis b vaccination rates as something of clinical interest, but also more manageable in the time frame of this project. Specifically, this project will aim to assess the impact of a QI/Safety Rounding Checklist - a clinical decision support tool - implemented across four NICUs on hepatitis b vaccination rates. This project will use deidentified EHR data (Epic, Clarity) and analysis will be done in aggregate to not reveal local site data.

Link to github: https://github.com/alexbruan/BMIN5030_Final_Project_Fork

2 Introduction

Describe the problem addressed, its significance, and some background to motivate the problem. This should extend what is in the SectionÂ 1.

Explain why your problem is interdisciplinary, what fields can contribute to its understanding, and incorporate background related to what you learned from meeting with faculty/staff.

There is a well-established body of research associating checklists with improved outcomes, from adherence to best practice guidelines, to decreased risk of infection, to improved preferred language documentation. (ref 1-4) While prior work in the Childrenâs Hospital of Philadelphia NICU has demonstrated success with Epic integration of a checklist, this was limited to a single quaternary academic unit. (ref 5)

In 2019, another local NICU, a level III NICU, implemented a REDCap-based checklist to support local quality improvement (QI) and safety initiatives, but compliance with the tool was less than 50%. A 2023 provider survey revealed low perceived relevance and high burden, with key barriers including workflow interruptions and tool accessibility. Feedback strongly supported Epic integration. The same instance of Epic is live in four NICUs in the same health system. Discussions with leadership of these NICUs revealed strong support for the design and implementation of a standardized network-wide tool, allowing for the development of an Epic-based CDS tool.

In the period of December 2024-March 2025, the four NICUs went live with this tool. Key results from this project include a statistically significant increase in the average biweekly compliance from 25% to 90% from October 2023 to October 2025 based on a statistical process control p-chart at a pilot NICU. Across all four NICUs, average compliance was 86% as of October 2025. Survey data (67% response rate, 66/98) indicated that most NICU clinicians found the tool easy to use, clinically relevant, and beneficial for patient safety.

While there has been data to show that such a tool supports clinical processes and workflows, it is unclear what effect it may have on clinical outcomes of interest. As such, this project will aim to assess the impact of a QI/Safety Rounding Checklist - a clinical decision support tool - implemented across four NICUs on hepatitis b vaccination rates. This project will use deidentified EHR data (Epic, Clarity) and analysis will be done in aggregate to not reveal local site data.

3 Methods

Describe the data used and general methodological approach used to address the problem described in the SectionÂ 2. Subsequently, incorporate full R code necessary to retrieve and clean data, and perform analysis. Be sure to include a description of code so that others (including your future self) can understand what you are doing and why.

This project utilizes deidentified EHR data from Epicâs Clarity, which is a relational database with a normalized data model. This data is transferred from Chronicles, which is a hierarchical database with real-time data. This data flows from Chronicles to Clarity based on institutional ETL processes.

All NICU patients from March 2019 through September 2025 will be included in this analysis. March 2019 was chosen as one of the NICUs previously had a REDCap based checklist that went live in March 2019. Moreover, recommendations for Hepatitis B vaccination timing depends on birth weight. The first dose should ideally be given within 24 hours of birth (though this may differ in the critical care setting) if birth weight >/= 2000 grams or first dose by 1 month of life or at time of discharge from the hospital if birth weight <2000 grams. For the purposes of this analysis, only the >/= 2000 gram cohort will be included. Given the CDS tool asks about vaccination once a week, and is not restricted based on any further logic built into the EHR, this analysis looks at if the patient received vaccination at two time points 1) within the first 7 days and 2) by the time of discharge. Basic demographic information will be included, such as birth weight, gestational age, race, ethnicity, and sex. Birth month and year is included to help determine if the patient was born pre/post CDS implementation. Clinical co-variates of interest, which are markers of clinical severity, are also included such as, vitamin k administration, pressors within 7 days, antibiotics within 7 days, diagnosis of hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy, intubated within 7 days, history of non-invasive respiratory support within 7 days, history of central line within 7 days. Patients who died were excluded. Patients who had mothers with a history of hepatitis b infection were excluded since they are treated different clinically from newborns without maternal history of infection (given hepatitis b vaccine and hepatitis b immunoglobulin within 12 hours of life). CDS tool use within 7 days as well as if it was used at all was also included. All of these columns were joined from various tables in Clarity so just one CSV is required to be loaded into R.

#clean data, excluding died during encounter, maternal hep b status, cleaning race, ethnicity, dates, sorting chronologically 
#cleaning of site data is in a separate hidden chunk to keep sites truly deidentified
hepb_clean <- hepb %>%
  filter(died_during_encounter == 0, maternal_hepb_status == 0) %>%
  mutate(
    sex = factor(sex, levels = c("Female", "Male")),
    birth_weight_category = as.factor(birth_weight_category),
    ga = as.numeric(na_if(ga_complete_weeks, "null")),
    race = case_when(
      str_detect(patient_race_all_lines, regex("Declined", ignore_case = TRUE)) |
        str_detect(patient_race_all_lines, regex("Unknown", ignore_case = TRUE)) |
        is.na(patient_race_all_lines) ~ "Declined/Unknown",
      str_detect(patient_race_all_lines, regex("Black or African American", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~
        "Black or African American",
      str_detect(patient_race_all_lines, regex("Asian", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "Asian",
      str_detect(patient_race_all_lines, regex("White", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "White",
      TRUE ~ "Other"
    ),
    race = factor(
      race,
      levels = c("White", "Black or African American", "Asian", "Other", "Declined/Unknown")
    ),
    ethnicity = case_when(
      patient_ethnic_group == "Hispanic Latino"        ~ "Hispanic Latino",
      patient_ethnic_group == "Not Hispanic or Latino" ~ "Not Hispanic or Latino",
      TRUE                                             ~ "Declined/Missing"
    ),
    ethnicity = factor(
      ethnicity,
      levels = c("Hispanic Latino", "Not Hispanic or Latino", "Declined/Missing")
    ),
    birth_month_year      = na_if(birth_month_year, "null"),
    birth_month_year_str  = sub("^(\\d{2})-(\\w{3})$", "01-\\2-20\\1", birth_month_year),
    month_year            = dmy(birth_month_year_str)
  ) %>%
  arrange(month_year) %>%  # sort chronologically
  select(
    -patient_ethnic_group,
    -patient_race_all_lines,
    -birth_month_year_str
  ) %>%
  filter_at(vars(ga, sex, birth_weight_grams), all_vars(!is.na(.)))

4.2 Data Visualization, Tool Use

# Monthly CDS tool use
tool_monthly <- hepb_clean %>%
  filter(post_cds_flag == 1) %>%
  group_by(month_year) %>%
  summarise(
    n_births       = n(),
    tool_use_rate  = mean(cds_tool_used_at_all, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups        = "drop"
  ) %>% arrange(month_year)

ggplot(tool_monthly, aes(x = month_year, y = tool_use_rate)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_date(
    date_labels = "%b %Y",  
    date_breaks = "1 month"   
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    labels = percent_format(accuracy = 1),
    limits = c(0, 1),
    breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)
  ) +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "CDS tool use (%)", title = "CDS Tool Use Over Time (Post-CDS Era Only)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

4.3 Data Visualization, Plotting Hepatitis B Vaccination Rate Over Time (March 2019 - September 2025)

4.6 Logistic Regression

#Create a high acuity column for logistic regression 
hepb_model <- hepb_clean %>%
  mutate(
    high_acuity = if_else(
      has_hie == 1 |
        intubated_within_7_days == 1 |
        noninvasive_within_7_days == 1 |
        central_line_within_7_days == 1 |
        pressor_within_7_days == 1 |
        abx_within_7_days == 1,
      1L, 0L
    ),
    high_acuity = factor(high_acuity, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("No", "Yes")),)

5 Conclusion

In various analyses, from chi-square analyses and multivariable logistic regression models, there was a statistically significant decrease in hepatitis b vaccination rate in the pre/post cohorts. For example, for the chi square chisq.test(tab_hepb), the p-value was 4.11x10-12 and for the logistic regression as shown in tidy_hepb_ever_prepost, the p-value for post CDS was 4.2x10-12 with an OR = 0.44 (CI: 0.35-0.55). Even when accounting for clinical severity, restricting to the post CDS era, and accounting for tool use this association held true as seen in the above analyses. Importantly, this is an association and not causation. Functionally and mechanistically, it is less probable that the implementation and use of a CDS tool that prompts providers to discuss vaccination would lead to less hepatitis b vaccines in the post CDS era. Indeed, when looking at the overall trend of the hepatitis b vaccination rate over time, it appears that there was a decreasing trend in the vaccine rates prior to the tool being implemented. This could be due to a number of factors including shifting parental attitudes towards vaccination and the political climate. It should also be stated that there are limitations with the data insofar as the post period has a relatively smaller sample size, and the expected effect size of this specific feature of the tool would be small, since it is not a targeted or âsmartâ nudge.

In addition to the declining vaccine rates, there were some other associations that were important to note and bear further discussion. Perhaps most important were the differences by race, with individuals who had Black/African American identities having a reduced odds of hepatitis b vaccination.

Overall, there was no clear impact of the CDS tool in light of declining hepatitis b vaccination rates. Moving forward, further analyses using quasi-experimental methodologies such as interrupted time series to model the direct impact of the tool may be worth considering.
